solution:
The long division is shown below.

\[
\begin{array}{c|cc ccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x^2} & -2x & +8 \\
\cline{2-6}
x^2 + 2x - 1 & x^4 & & +3x^2 & -7x &  \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x^4} & +2x^3 & -x^2 \\
\cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -2x^3 & +4x^2 & -7x \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -2x^3 & -4x^2 & +2x \\
\cline{3-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & +8x^2 & -9x & \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} &  & +8x^2 & +16x & -8 \\
\cline{4-6}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} &  &  & -25x & +8 \\
\end{array}
\]Thus, the quotient is $\boxed{x^2 - 2x + 8}.$

Rearranging $x^2 - x - 1= 0$ gives $x^2 = x + 1$.  So, repeatedly substituting $x+1$ for $x^2$ gives us \begin{align*}
x^3 - 2x + 1 &= x(x^2)-2x + 1\\
&=x(x+1) - 2x + 1\\
&= x^2 + x -2x + 1\\
&= x^2 - x + 1\\
&= (x+1) - x + 1\\
&=\boxed{2}
\end{align*}

Instead of expanding the entire product, we can look only at terms that will multiply to give $x^3$.  We know that: $$x^3=x^3\cdot 1=x^2\cdot x=x\cdot x^2=1\cdot x^3$$Knowing this, the $x^3$ term in the expansion will be the sum of these four terms: $$(-3x^3)(4)+(-3x^2)(3x)+(-8x)(-7x^2)+(1)(2x^3)$$We simplify to find: \begin{align*}
&(-3x^3)(4)+(-3x^2)(3x)+(-8x)(-7x^2)+(1)(2x^3)\\
&\qquad=-12x^3-9x^3+56x^3+2x^3\\
&\qquad=\boxed{37}x^3
\end{align*}

