label("$3$", (A + D)/2, E);
label("$4$", (B + C)/2, S);
label("$5$", interp(B,D,0.75), NW);
[/asy]

Since $D$ is the mid-point of $\overline{AC},$ $AD = 3.$  Hence,
\[\tan \angle ABC = \frac{6}{4} = \boxed{\frac{3}{2}}.\]

By the Angle Bisector Theorem,
\[\frac{BD}{AB} = \frac{CD}{AC},\]or $\frac{BD}{6} = \frac{AC}{3},$ so $BD = 2CD.$  Let $x = CD$; then $BD = 2x.$

[asy]
unitsize (0.8 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

B = (0,0);
C = (3*sqrt(7),0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc(B,6,0,180),arc(C,3,0,180));
D = interp(B,C,2/3);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
